shire, England","Stockland, Dorset, England":"Stockland with Dalwood, Dorset, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mitchell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the vernacular pronunciation in Middle English and Older Scots of the personal name   Michael  . See   Michelson  .","English and Scottish: nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>michel</i>, <i>mechel</i>, <i>muchel</i> ‘big’.","Irish (County Connacht): surname adopted as equivalent of   Mulvihill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Michell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Etienne, Yvrose.","English (Cornwall): variant of   Mitchell   and   Michel  .","German: variant of   Michel  . This surname is rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Mutch","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire) and English (Lancashire and Cheshire): nickname for a large (tall or fat) person, from Middle English <i>moche</i>, <i>muche</i> ‘big’ (a shortened form of <i>mochel</i>, <i>muchel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Muckle  ."]},{"name":"Meikle","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Middle Scots <i>mekill</i>, <i>meikill</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell   2,   Muckle  , and   Mutch  ."]},{"name":"Mickle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Mutch  .","Americanized form of German   Mickel   1 or of a homonymous Germanized Sorbian surname (see   Mickel   2)."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."]},{"name":"Mitchel","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Mixell","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Muckle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’ (Old English <i>mycel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle   and   Mutch  .","South German: from a diminutive of   Muck   ‘gnat’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Mitchell was born in 1505, in Perthshire, Scotland. He had at least 1 son with Ann Vye. He died in 1550, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1518–1534":"1518–1534","1534–1614":"1534–1614","1534":"1534","1550":"1550","1518":"1518","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stockland, Dorset, England":"Stockland with Dalwood, Dorset, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1518–1534":"1518–1534","1534–1614":"1534–1614","1534":"1534","1550":"1550","1518":"1518","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stockland, Dorset, England":"Stockland with Dalwood, Dorset, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1518–1534":"1518–1534","1534–1614":"1534–1614","1534":"1534","1550":"1550","1518":"1518","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Stockland, Dorset, England":"Stockland with Dalwood, Dorset, Angleterre","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Thomas Mitchell est né en 1505, à Perthshire, Écosse. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Ann Vye. Il est décédé en 1550, à Everwyck, Angleterre, à l’âge de 45 ans."},"de":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1518–1534":"1518–1534","1534–1614":"1534–1614","1534":"1534","1550":"1550","1518":"1518","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stockland, Dorset, England":"Stockland with Dalwood, Dorset, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","lifeSummary":"Thomas Mitchell wurde 1505 in Perthshire, Scotland geboren. Er hatte mit Ann Vye mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1550 im Alter von 45 Jahren in Yorkshire, England."},"ht":{"1505–1550":"1505–15